GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 1
SENATE BILL 421
Short Title: Prison Reform Omnibus. (Public)
Sponsors: Senator Applewhite (Primary Sponsor).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
March 25, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO REFORM PRISON LABOR LAWS IN NORTH CAROLINA TO ENSURE FAIR
3 COMPENSATION, MEANINGFUL REHABILITATION, EQUITABLE WORK
4 OPPORTUNITIES, AND PROTECTIONS AGAINST LABOR EXPLOITATION.
5 Whereas, the current statutory framework governing prison labor in North Carolina
6 prioritizes State cost-savings over rehabilitation and workforce readiness; and
7 Whereas, national best practices, including New York, Maryland, and the Prison
8 Industry Enhancement Certification Program (PIECP), provide models for fair, rehabilitative,
9 and economically beneficial prison labor policies; and
10 Whereas, ninety-four percent (94%) of incarcerated individuals will reenter society,
11 and equipping them with vocational skills, fair wages, and work experience is essential for
12 reducing recidivism and increasing public safety; and
13 Whereas, the North Carolina agricultural industry is facing labor shortages, and prison
14 labor must not be exploited as a replacement for migrant or seasonal workers; and
15 Whereas, transparency, oversight, and independent auditing are critical to ensuring
16 prison labor programs serve the interests of rehabilitation, workforce development, and ethical
17 labor standards; and
18 Whereas, strengthening employment placement programs and offering tax incentives
19 to businesses hiring formerly incarcerated individuals will enhance North Carolina's economy
20 and reduce recidivism; Now, therefore,
21 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
22 SECTION 1. The following sections of Article 3 of Chapter 148 of the General
23 Statutes are repealed:
24 (1) G.S. 148-26.
25 (2) G.S. 148-26.1.
26 (3) G.S. 148-26.5.
27 (4) G.S. 148-32.2.
28 (5) G.S. 148-32.3.
29 (6) G.S. 148-33.
30 SECTION 2. Article 3 of Chapter 148 of the General Statutes, as amended by
31 Section 1 of this act, reads as rewritten:
32 "Article 3.
33 "Labor of Prisoners.Fair and Rehabilitative Prison Labor Act.
34 "§ 148-27.1. State policy on employment of incarcerated individuals.
35 (a) It is the policy of the State of North Carolina that all incarcerated individuals who are
36 medically and physically fit, as determined by a licensed healthcare professional, may be
*S421-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 provided with voluntary work opportunities that are rehabilitative, workforce-oriented, and fairly
2 compensated.
3 (b) Work programs under this Article shall do each of the following:
4 (1) Prioritize training and skill development in industries with viable employment
5 opportunities upon release.
6 (2) Ensure that prison labor is not used to displace non-incarcerated workers,
7 including migrant and seasonal agricultural workers.
8 (3) Comply with labor standards set forth in the Prison Industry Enhancement
9 Certification Program (PIECP), ensuring prevailing wage standards where
10 applicable.
11 (4) Offer meaningful vocational education, apprenticeship, and certification
12 programs.
13 (5) Establish gender-equitable labor policies, ensuring access to diverse work
14 opportunities for both male and female incarcerated individuals.
15 (6) Provide fair compensation, with wages at least equal to the State minimum
16 wage for PIECP-certified programs and no less than five dollars ($5.00) per
17 hour for non-PIECP programs.
18 (7) Ensure incarcerated individuals are provided post-release employment
19 assistance in collaboration with the North Carolina Department of Commerce,
20 workforce development boards, and private employers.
21 "§ 148-27.2. Definitions.
22 Unless otherwise specified or understood from the surrounding context, the following
23 definitions apply in this Article:
24 (1) Division. – The Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction.
25 (2) Incarcerated individual. – A person in the custody of the Department of Adult
26 Correction or any other State or law enforcement agency, often referred to as
27 an inmate or prisoner.
28 (3) PIECP. – The Prison Industry Enhancement Certification Program.
29 (4) Secretary. – The Secretary of the Department of Adult Correction.
30 "§ 148-27.3. Prohibition on using prison labor to replace agricultural and private-sector
31 workers.
32 (a) No prison labor shall be used to replace, displace, or supplement migrant, seasonal,
33 or documented agricultural workers who have been affected by State or federal immigration
34 enforcement actions.
35 (b) Before approving any prison labor contracts in the agricultural sector, the North
36 Carolina Department of Labor shall conduct a labor market assessment to confirm a legitimate
37 labor shortage exists.
38 (c) Any incarcerated individual engaged in agricultural work shall be compensated at or
39 above the prevailing wage for agricultural laborers in the State.
40 (d) Private farms are prohibited from contracting directly with any representative or
41 entity of the Department of Adult Correction for prison labor.
42 (e) No later than March 1 and September 1 of each year, the Department of Adult
43 Correction shall report to the Governor and General Assembly regarding the use of incarcerated
44 individuals in agricultural labor, including, at a minimum, all of the following information:
45 (1) Total hours worked by incarcerated individuals during the current and
46 previous calendar year.
47 (2) Total and individual wages paid to incarcerated individuals during the current
48 and previous calendar year.
49 (3) Number of non-incarcerated agricultural jobs affected by the use of prison
50 labor pursuant to this Article during the current and previous calendar year.
