9 "§ 148-32.4. Oversight of Department of Transportation and forestry work assignments.
10 (a) No later than March 1 and September 1 of each year, the Department of Adult
11 Correction, in consultation with the Department of Transportation (DOT) and the North Carolina
12 Forest Service, shall report to the Governor and General Assembly regarding the work of
13 incarcerated individuals on DOT and forestry work assignments, including, at a minimum, all of
14 the following information:
15 (1) Total hours worked by incarcerated individuals.
16 (2) Wages paid and any deductions applied.
17 (3) Estimated cost-savings to the State compared to civilian labor costs.
18 (4) Work site safety measures implemented.
19 (5) Skill certifications and job placements available to incarcerated workers upon
20 release.
21 (b) No incarcerated individual shall be compelled to work in road maintenance,
22 construction, or forestry without voluntary participation and fair wages.
23 (c) Any forestry, conservation, or wildfire suppression work performed by incarcerated
24 individuals shall provide industry-recognized certification opportunities in firefighting, land
25 management, and forestry to improve post-release employability.
26 (d) Medical assessments for DOT and forestry work shall include, at a minimum, each of
27 the following requirements:
28 (1) No incarcerated individual shall be assigned physically demanding labor
29 based on outward physical appearance alone.
30 (2) Eligibility for DOT and forestry work shall be based on a comprehensive
31 medical evaluation conducted by a licensed healthcare professional.
32 (e) The Prison Labor Oversight Board created by G.S. 148-32.5 shall conduct an annual
33 audit of DOT and forestry work programs to ensure compliance with fair labor standards,
34 workforce training goals, and public transparency requirements.
35 "§ 148-32.5. Independent oversights, public transparency, and worker protections.
36 (a) A Prison Labor Oversight Board shall be established within the Department of Adult
37 Correction to do each of the following:
38 (1) Conduct annual audits of all prison labor programs.
39 (2) Ensure compliance with PIECP standards and fair wage requirements.
40 (3) Investigate allegations of forced labor, unsafe working conditions, or wage
41 exploitation.
42 (b) No later than March 1 and September 1 of each year, the Department of Adult
43 Correction shall report to the Governor and General Assembly regarding the work of incarcerated
44 individuals, including, at a minimum, all of the following information:
45 (1) The types of work assignments offered to incarcerated individuals.
46 (2) The total revenue generated from prison labor contracts.
47 (3) Job placement rates of formerly incarcerated individuals who participated in
48 work programs.
49 (4) The overall impact of prison labor programs on North Carolina's economy and
50 workforce development efforts.
