1 thereto to those sites and erect necessary buildings thereon, on those sites and lands, or purchase
2 or lease existing facilities, all within the limits of allotments as approved by the Department of
3 Administration.
4 (b) The Secretary of the Department of Adult Correction may contract with the proper
5 official of the United States or of any county or city of this State for the confinement of federal
6 prisoners incarcerated individuals after they have been sentenced, county, or city prisoners
7 incarcerated individuals in facilities of the State prison system or for the confinement of State
8 prisoners incarcerated individuals in any county or any city facility located in North Carolina, or
9 any facility of the United States Bureau of Prisons, when to do so would most economically and
10 effectively promote the purposes served by the Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult
11 Correction. Except as otherwise provided, any contract made under the authority of this
12 subsection shall be for a period of not more than two years, and shall be renewable from time to
13 time for a period not to exceed two years. Contracts made under the authority of this subsection
14 for the confinement of State prisoners incarcerated individuals in local or district confinement
15 facilities may be for a period of not more than 10 years and renewable from time to time for a
16 period not to exceed 10 years, and shall be subject to the approval of the Council of State and the
17 Department of Administration after consultation with the Joint Legislative Commission on
18 Governmental Operations. Contracts for receiving federal, county and city prisoners incarcerated
19 individuals shall provide for reimbursing the State in full for all costs involved. The financial
20 provisions shall have the approval of the Department of Administration before the contract is
21 executed. Payments received under such these contracts shall be deposited in the State treasury
22 for the use of the Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction. Such These
23 payments are hereby shall be appropriated to the Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult
24 Correction as a supplementary fund to compensate for the additional care and maintenance of
25 such the prisoners as are received under such these contracts.
26 …
27 (c) In addition to the authority contained in subsections (a) and (b) of this section, and in
28 addition to the contracts ratified by subsection (f) of this section, the Secretary of the Department
29 of Adult Correction may enter into contracts with any public entity or any private nonprofit or
30 for-profit firms for the confinement and care of State prisoners incarcerated individuals in any
31 out-of-state correctional facility when to do so would most economically and effectively promote
32 the purposes served by the Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction. Contracts
33 entered into under the authority of this subsection shall be for a period not to exceed two years
34 and shall be renewable from time to time for a period not to exceed two years. Prisoners
35 Incarcerated individuals may be sent to out-of-state correctional facilities only when there are no
36 available facilities in this State within the State prison system to appropriately house those
37 prisoners. incarcerated individuals. Any contract made under the authority of this subsection shall
38 be approved by the Department of Administration before the contract is executed. Before
39 expending more than the amount specifically appropriated by the General Assembly for the
40 out-of-state housing of inmates, incarcerated individuals, the Division shall obtain the approval
41 of the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations and shall report such
42 expenditures to the Chairs of the Senate and House Appropriations Committees, the Chairs of
43 the Senate and House Appropriations Subcommittees on Justice and Public Safety, and the Chairs
44 of the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Justice and Public Safety.
45 (d) Prisoners Incarcerated individuals confined in out-of-state correctional facilities
46 pursuant to subsection (c) of this section shall remain subject to the rules adopted for the conduct
47 of persons committed to the State prison system. The rules regarding good time and gain time,
48 discipline, classification, extension of the limits of confinement, transfers, housing arrangements,
49 and eligibility for parole shall apply to inmates incarcerated individuals housed in those
50 out-of-state correctional facilities. The operators of those out-of-state correctional facilities may
51 promulgate any other rules as may be necessary for the operation of those facilities with the
