12 (g) The Secretary of the Department of Adult Correction may contract with private
13 for-profit or nonprofit firms for the provision and operation of four or more confinement facilities
14 totaling up to 2,000 beds in the State to house State prisoners incarcerated individuals when to
15 do so would most economically and effectively promote the purposes served by the Division of
16 Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction. This 2,000-bed limitation shall not apply to the
17 500 beds in private substance abuse treatment centers authorized by the General Assembly prior
18 to July 1, 1995. Whenever the Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction
19 determines that new prison facilities are required in addition to existing and planned facilities,
20 the Division may contract for any remaining beds authorized by this section before constructing
21 State-operated facilities.
22 Contracts entered under the authority of this subsection shall be for a period not to exceed 10
23 years, shall be renewable from time to time for a period not to exceed 10 years. The Secretary of
24 the Department of Adult Correction shall enter contracts under this subsection only if funds are
25 appropriated for this purpose by the General Assembly. Contracts entered under the authority of
26 this subsection may be subject to any requirements for the location of the confinement facilities
27 set forth by the General Assembly in appropriating those funds.
28 Once the Division has made a determination to contract for additional private prison beds, it
29 shall issue a request for proposals within 30 days of the decision. The request for proposals shall
30 require bids to be submitted within two months, and the Division shall award contracts at the
31 earliest practicable date after the submission of bids. The Secretary of the Department of Adult
32 Correction, in consultation with the Chairs of the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on
33 Justice and Public Safety and the Chairs of the House and Senate Appropriations Subcommittees
34 on Justice and Public Safety, shall make recommendations to the State Purchasing Officer on the
35 final award decision. The State Purchasing Officer shall make the final award decision, and the
36 contract shall then be subject to the approval of the Council of State after consultation with the
37 Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations.
38 Contracts made under the authority of this subsection may provide the State with an option
39 to purchase the confinement facility or may provide for the purchase of the confinement facility
40 by the State. Contracts made under the authority of this subsection shall state that plans and
41 specifications for private confinement facilities shall be furnished to and reviewed by the Office
42 of State Construction. The Office of State Construction shall inspect and review each project
43 during construction to ensure that the project is suitable for habitation and to determine whether
44 the project would be suitable for future acquisition by the State. All contracts for the housing of
45 State prisoners incarcerated individuals in private confinement facilities shall require a minimum
46 of ten million dollars ($10,000,000) of occurrence-based liability insurance and shall hold the
47 State harmless and provide reimbursement for all liability arising out of actions caused by
48 operations and employees of the private confinement facility.
49 Prisoners Incarcerated individuals housed in private confinement facilities pursuant to this
50 subsection shall remain subject to the rules adopted for the conduct of persons committed to the
51 State prison system. The Secretary of the Department of Adult Correction may review and
