21 "§ 148-37.1. Prohibition on private prisons housing out-of-state inmates.incarcerated
22 individuals.
23 (a) Except as otherwise provided in this section or authorized by North Carolina law, no
24 municipality, county, or private entity may authorize, construct, own, or operate any type of
25 correctional facility for the confinement of inmates incarcerated individuals serving sentences
26 for violation of the laws of a jurisdiction other than North Carolina.
27 (b) The provisions of this section shall not apply to facilities owned or operated by the
28 federal government and used exclusively for the confinement of inmates incarcerated individuals
29 serving sentences for violation of federal law, but only to the extent that such those facilities are
30 not subject to restriction by the states under the provisions of the United States Constitution.
31 "§ 148-37.3. Authority of private correctional officers employed pursuant to a contract
32 with the Federal Bureau of Prisons.
33 (a) Correctional officers and security supervisors employed at private correctional
34 facilities pursuant to a contract between their employer and the Federal Bureau of Prisons may,
35 in the course of their employment as correctional officers or security supervisors, use necessary
36 force and make arrests consistent with the laws applicable to the Division of Prisons of the
37 Department of Adult Correction, which force shall not exceed that authorized to Division of
38 Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction officers, provided that the employment policies
39 of such those private corporations meet the same minimum standards and practices followed by
40 the Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction in employing its correctional
41 personnel, and if:if either of the following circumstances applies:
42 (1) Those correctional officers and security supervisors have been certified as
43 correctional officers as provided under Article 1 of Chapter 17C of the
44 General Statutes; orStatutes.
45 (2) Those correctional officers and security supervisors employed by the private
46 corporation at the facility have completed a training curriculum that meets or
47 exceeds the standards required by the North Carolina Criminal Justice
48 Education and Training Standards Commission for correctional personnel.
49 …
50 (c) Any private corporation described in subsection (a) of this section shall reimburse the
51 State and any county or other law enforcement agency for the full cost of any additional expenses
