18 (f) Any person convicted of an escape or attempt to escape classified as a felony by this
19 section shall be immediately classified and treated as a convicted felon even if such the person
20 has time remaining to be served in the State prison system on a sentence or sentences imposed
21 upon conviction of a misdemeanor or misdemeanors.
22 (g) (1) Any person convicted and in the custody of the Division of Prisons of the
23 Department of Adult Correction and ordered or otherwise assigned to work
24 under the work-release program, G.S. 148-33.1, or any convicted person in
25 the custody of the Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction
26 and temporarily allowed to leave a place of confinement by the Secretary of
27 the Department of Adult Correction or his the Secretary's designee or other
28 authority of law, who shall fail to return to the custody of the Division of
29 Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction, shall be guilty of the crime of
30 escape and subject to the applicable provisions of this section and shall be
31 deemed an escapee. For the purpose of this subsection, escape is defined to
32 include, but is not restricted to, willful failure to return to an appointed place
33 and at an appointed time as ordered.
34 (2) If a person, who would otherwise be guilty of a first violation of
35 G.S. 148-45(g)(1), voluntarily returns to his place of confinement within 24
36 hours of the time at which he the person was ordered to return, such that person
37 shall not be charged with an escape as provided in this section but shall be
38 subject to such administrative action as may be deemed appropriate for an
39 escapee by the Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction;
40 said that escapee shall not be allowed to be placed on work release for a
41 four-month period or for the balance of his the escapee's term if less than four
42 months; provided, however, that if such that person commits a subsequent
43 violation of this section then such that person shall be charged with that
44 offense and, if convicted, punished under the provisions of this section.
45 "§ 148-46. Degree of protection against violence allowed.
46 (a) When any prisoner, incarcerated individual, or several combined combined, shall
47 offer violence to any officer, overseer, or correctional officer, or to any fellow prisoner,
48 incarcerated individual, or attempt to do any injury to the prison building, or to any workshop,
49 or other equipment, or shall attempt to escape, or shall resist, or disobey any lawful command,
50 the officer, overseer, or correctional officer shall use any means necessary to defend himself, or
Senate Bill 421-First Edition Page 15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 to enforce the observance of discipline, or to secure the person of the offender, and to prevent an
2 escape.
3 (b) A misdemeanor prisoner incarcerated individual classified and treated as a convicted
4 felon as the result of a consecutive felony sentence or sentences, or a convicted felon placed in
5 the custody of the Secretary of the Department of Adult Correction pending the outcome of an
6 appeal, or a defendant charged with a felony or felonies and placed in the custody of the Secretary
7 of the Department of Adult Correction pending trial, shall be considered as a convicted felon in
8 the custody of the Secretary of the Department of Adult Correction against whom any means
9 reasonably necessary, including deadly force, may be used to prevent an escape.
10 "§ 148-46.1. Inflicting or assisting in infliction of self injury to prisoner an incarcerated
11 individual resulting in incapacity to perform assigned duties.
12 Any person serving a sentence or sentences within the State prison system who, during the
13 term of such imprisonment, willfully and intentionally inflicts upon himself any injury resulting
14 in a permanent or temporary incapacity to perform work or duties assigned to him that person by
15 the Division of Prisons of the Department of Adult Correction, or any prisoner incarcerated
16 individual who aids or abets any other prisoner incarcerated individual in the commission of such
17 offense, shall be punished as a Class H felon.
18 "§ 148-46.2. Procedure when consent is refused by prisoner.an incarcerated individual.
19 When the Secretary of the Department of Adult Correction finds as a fact that the injury to
20 any prisoner incarcerated individual was willfully and intentionally self-inflicted and that an
21 operation or treatment is necessary for the preservation or restoration of the health of the prisoner
22 incarcerated individual and that the prisoner incarcerated individual is competent to act for
23 himself or herself; and that attempts have been made to obtain consent for the proposed operation
24 or treatment but such the consent was refused, and the findings have been reduced to writing and
25 entered into the prisoner's incarcerated individual's records as a permanent part thereof, of those
26 records, then the chief medical officer of the prison hospital or prison institution shall be
27 authorized to give or withhold, on behalf of the prisoner, incarcerated individual, consent to the
28 operation or treatment.
29 In all cases coming under the provisions of this section, the medical staff of the hospital or
30 institution shall keep a careful and complete medical record of the treatment and surgical
31 procedures undertaken. The record shall be signed by the chief medical officer of the hospital or
32 institution and the surgeon performing any surgery. Any treatment of self-inflicted injuries shall
33 also be subject to the provisions of G.S. 90-21.13 and G.S. 90-21.16.
34 "§ 148-47. Disposition of child born of female prisoner.incarcerated individual.
35 Any child born of a female prisoner incarcerated individual while she the individual is in
36 custody shall as soon as practicable be surrendered to the director of social services of the county
37 wherein where the child was born upon a proper order of the domestic relations court or juvenile
38 court of said that county affecting the custody of said the child. When it appears to be for the best
39 interest of the child, the court may place custody beyond the geographical bounds of Wake
40 County: Provided, however, that all subsequent proceedings and orders affecting custody of said
41 the child shall be within the jurisdiction of the proper court of the county where the infant is
42 residing at the time such the proceeding is commenced or such the order is sought: Provided,
43 further, that nothing in this section shall affect the right of the mother to consent to the adoption
44 of her the child nor shall the right of the mother to place her the child with the legal father or
45 other suitable relative be affected by the provisions of this section.
46 "§ 148-48. Parole powers of Parole Commission unaffected.
47 Nothing in this Chapter shall be construed to limit or restrict the power of the Parole
48 Commission to parole prisoners incarcerated individuals under such conditions as it may impose
49 or prevent the reimprisonment of such prisoners incarcerated individuals upon violation of the
50 conditions of such that parole, as now provided by law.
